Wash and dry all produce. Bring @water{1 1/4%cups} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil in a #small pot{}. Halve, peel, and finely dice @yellow onion{1}. Drain and rinse @kidney beans{1%box}. Core and seed @poblano pepper{1}, then cut into ½-inch squares. Thinly slice @scallions{2}, keeping greens and whites separate. Slice @jalapeño{1} into rounds, removing ribs and seeds first for less heat. Dice @dried chorizo{2%oz} into small cubes.

Once water is boiling, add @jasmine rice{3/4%cup} to #pot{}. Cover, lower heat, and reduce to a gentle simmer. Cook until tender, about ~{15%minutes}. Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground beef{10%oz} and half the @enchilada spice blend{1%tablespoon}, breaking up meat into pieces. Cook, tossing, until browned and cooked through, about ~{6%minutes}. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Remove beef from pan and set aside. Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add onion, poblano, and scallion whites and give everything a toss. Stir in chorizo and remaining enchilada spice and cook, tossing, until veggies are softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir @beef stock concentrate{1}, beans, @crushed tomatoes{1%box}, and 1 cup water into veggie mixture in pan. Bring to a boil, then lower heat and reduce to a simmer. Stir in beef and continue simmering until thick and saucy, ~{5-10%minutes}. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Fluff rice with a #fork{}, then season with salt and pepper.

Divide half the rice between #bowls{} or #plates{}, then add half the chili to the side. Dollop with @sour cream{2%tablespoons} and ¼ of the @cheddar cheese{1%box}. Garnish with scallion greens and a few jalapeño slices (to taste). Tear half the @cilantro{1/4%oz} leaves from stems and scatter over top (save a bit of everything for lunch).

== For Lunch ==

When packing your lunch, slice @roma tomato{1} into rounds. Divide tomato, @flour tortillas{2}, and remaining sour cream, cheddar, chili, rice, jalapeño, and cilantro between #lunchboxes{}, keeping everything separate. When you're ready to eat, warm chili in #microwave{}. Spread sour cream on one side of a tortilla, then fill with ingredients from your lunch box. Roll to make burritos.

> This recipe makes extras that can easily be heated up, even at the office - your coworkers will be amazed, trust us!